{
  "texts": [
    "We can define the action of this spectral flow automorphism σ by [7] σ(ξ ± r) = ξ ± r∓1/2, σ(η ± r) = η ± r∓1/2, σ(ψ ± r) = ψ ± r±1/2, σ(χ ± r) = χ ± r±1/2.States in the w-spectrally flowed representation are denoted by [|m 1, m 2 ⟩] σ w, on which an operator A r acts asA r [|m 1, m 2 ⟩] σ w ≡ [σ w (A r)|m 1, m 2 ⟩] σ w.Because we are working with the free field realisation, which realises the full u(1, 1|2) 1 algebra before the quotient in (2.5), there exists a second spectral flow automorphism, denoted by σ. Whilst σ acts non-trivially only on psu(1, 1|2) 1 ⊂ u(1, 1|2) 1 which is the physical part of the theory we care about, the automorphism σ acts non-trivially on the U(1) charges U and V. To be explicit,σ(ξ ± r) = ξ ± r+1/2, σ(η ± r) = η ± r-1/2, σ(ψ ± r) = ψ ± r-1/2, σ(χ ± r) = χ ± r+1/2.",
    "(3.2)Spectrally flowed representations are generically not highest weight, yet it turns out that the σ2 -spectrally flowed representation is the vacuum representation with respect to psu(1, 1|2) 1 [7].",
    "The vacuum state |0⟩ (1) = [ψ + -3/2 ψ - -3/2 ψ + -1/2 ψ - -1/2 |0⟩]σ2 has a Y 0 eigenvalue of 2, in contrast to the vacuum of the unflowed representation which has a Y 0 eigenvalue of 0.",
    "This is because of the non-trivial action of σ on the two U(1) charges.",
    "We denote the vertex operator corresponding to the σ2 vacuum by W (z) and this will be useful later in section 3.3 for fixing the picture number of Y in physical correlation functions."
  ]
}